{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1774458125,"nonce":"HQWo+358zxkjpmcz+q5ZjHaAOXI=","title":"Part 1 analysis: plant perturbation responses (curl field)","message":"Umbrella: 297260c (Part 1)\n\n**Motivation:** Assess robustness to environmental disturbances by measuring reaching performance under velocity-dependent curl force fields of varying amplitude. This is the primary test of whether adversarial training produces genuinely robust controllers.\n\n**Approach:** Insert curl field intervenors at varying amplitudes into the plant mechanics. Evaluate reaching performance using aligned trajectory profiles, effector trajectory plots, and scalar measures (forces, velocities, deviations, endpoint errors). Compare models trained at different perturbation std levels.\n\n**Status:** Module exists at `src/rlrmp/modules/analysis/part1/plant_perts.py`. Rich analysis pipeline with aligned trajectories (by pert amp and by train std), time-series profiles, and multi-measure violin plots.\n\n**References:** Shadmehr \u0026 Mussa-Ivaldi (1994) for curl field paradigm.","files":null}]}